{
  "answer": "**Ghalib's ghazal \"Dil-e-naadaan tujhe hua kya hai\" (from *Diwan-e-Ghalib*, chapter 36) opens by directly addressing the \"foolish heart\" (*dil-e-naadaan*) with two questions:**[^1]\n\n> My foolish heart, what's led you to this sway?  \n> For this deep pain, what is the healing way? Pray, what is it?\n\nThis sets the tone for the rest of the poem, which repeats the refrain \"Pray, what is it?\" (*yeh kya hai?*) as the speaker questions unrequited love, divine will, beauty, nature, loyalty, and even his own poetic worth.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 36 (\"Dil-e-naadaan tujhe hua kya hai\"), [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/36-dil-e-naadaan-tujhe-hua-kya-hai/translation/#p-414b38).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 36 (\"Dil-e-naadaan tujhe hua kya hai\"), [paragraphs](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/36-dil-e-naadaan-tujhe-hua-kya-hai/translation/#p-29725b#p-1a9614).",
